<subSubSection id="8F29A9B11F01A1C5B1978D74C29D7021" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5B4A0E71AB4D53119AF8C16635F93112" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE86B4380B9D5F745B66E3EE2965BB65" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
For a detailed description, see 
<bibRefCitation id="D75139A6EA1EF3BC8C0B26E27F8208C9" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="3 - 326" refId="B60" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2019. Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths. Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano 46: 3 - 326" title="Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths." volume="46" year="2019">Schwarzhans (2019)</bibRefCitation>
and the subsequent update in 
<bibRefCitation id="4691DF53D5E3F5BCA5E25A7A06877950" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" author="Schwarzhans, WW" journalOrPublisher="Paleobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" refId="B63" refString="Schwarzhans, WW, Nielsen, SN, 2021. Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e16. [62 pp] https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" title="Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e 16. [62 pp]" url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" year="2021">Schwarzhans and Nielsen (2021)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="307CA334B4765E74714C48AC51C039E8" authorityName="Schwarzhans" authorityYear="2019" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Protomyctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protomyctophum ahunga" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ahunga">
<emphasis id="8CA21E5274C4A83F5496BE5359EF9D3C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Protomyctophum ahunga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a typical and rather common species in the late Burdigalian of New Zealand and Chile but has not been found in coeval sediments of the Caribbean (Trinidad or Venezuela). Its common occurrence in late Burdigalian to early Langhian sediments of Japan indicates that it may have had an antitropical distribution in the Pacific Ocean during the late early and early middle Miocene.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AFBB3629B8A73F9AD8414B761EDF8C9D" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
